have long surpassed the abilities of even the best&nbsp;
human players of these games. And of course there&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:48.680 --> 00:03:55.320
are many more examples. The point is that AI is a&nbsp;
very wide field with countless applications. And&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:55.320 --> 00:04:00.520
AI is only growing in importance thanks to an&nbsp;
increase in computing power, the availability&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:00.520 --> 00:04:08.680
of big data, and breakthroughs in AI research,&nbsp;
such as the AI boom since ChatGPT’s release.

00:04:08.680 --> 00:04:14.280
Next, let’s dive deeper to examine machine&nbsp;
learning. Machine learning, or ML, is a subset of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:14.280 --> 00:04:19.520
artificial intelligence that focuses on enabling&nbsp;
computers to learn from data and improve their&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:19.520 --> 00:04:24.800
performance over time without needing explicit&nbsp;
programming. Instead of relying on hard-coded&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:24.800 --> 00:04:30.000
instructions from a human, machine learning&nbsp;
algorithms identify patterns in data and use&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:30.000 --> 00:04:36.440
those patterns to make predictions or decisions.&nbsp;
To put it in context, this blue box represents the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:36.440 --> 00:04:44.200
field of AI, and ML is a subset of that field. Not&nbsp;
all AI uses machine learning, but it’s one of the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:44.200 --> 00:04:51.080
most impactful components of modern AI. So, how&nbsp;
does machine learning work. Let’s break it down.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:51.080 --> 00:04:57.480
At a very high level, it can be broken down into&nbsp;
three parts. This represents the system, or model,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:57.480 --> 00:05:03.280
that we want to train with machine learning. The&nbsp;
learning starts with input data. This could be&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:03.280 --> 00:05:09.520
anything from numbers in a spreadsheet to&nbsp;
images, videos, or text. That data is used&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:09.520 --> 00:05:14.480
to train a model, meaning the machine learning&nbsp;
algorithm processes the data to learn patterns or&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:14.480 --> 00:05:20.400
relationships within it. Once trained, the model&nbsp;
can use what it has learned to make predictions or&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:20.400 --> 00:05:26.760
decisions when new data is provided. This cycle,&nbsp;
learning from data and applying what’s learned,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:26.760 --> 00:05:33.080
is what makes ML so powerful. Machine learning&nbsp;
powers many AI applications you already use,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:33.080 --> 00:05:39.120
including those listed in the previous slide.&nbsp;
For example, email spam filtering uses machine&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:39.120 --> 00:05:44.240
learning to identify unwanted messages.&nbsp;
Personalized product recommendations learn&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:44.240 --> 00:05:49.920
from your previous behavior help you find items&nbsp;
you’ll probably want to buy. Fraud detection&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:49.920 --> 00:05:56.000
in banking uses previous data to identify&nbsp;
and prevent suspicious activity. It’s also&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:56.000 --> 00:06:01.520
behind advanced techniques in natural language&nbsp;
processing, which enables computers to process and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:01.520 --> 00:06:07.760
understand human language. And of course, there&nbsp;
are plenty more examples. Although, as I said,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:07.760 --> 00:06:13.960
not all AI uses machine learning, it is the&nbsp;
driving force behind many modern AI applications.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:13.960 --> 00:06:22.480
AI as sophisticated as ChatGPT, for example,&nbsp;
wouldn’t be possible without machine learning.

00:06:22.480 --> 00:06:27.560
Now that we know the basics of machine learning,&nbsp;
let’s look at the four main types. First,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:27.560 --> 00:06:32.560
supervised learning. This is where the model&nbsp;
is trained on labeled data, meaning the correct&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:32.560 --> 00:06:38.040
answers are provided during training. The model&nbsp;
uses this data to learn and make predictions or&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:38.040 --> 00:06:44.760
classifications on new data. Next, unsupervised&nbsp;
learning. In this type, the model is given&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:44.760 --> 00:06:50.280
unlabeled data, and its goal is to find patterns,&nbsp;
relationships, or groupings within the data.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:50.280 --> 00:06:56.040
It’s a more hands-off approach. Then, we have&nbsp;
reinforcement learning. Here, the model learns&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:56.040 --> 00:07:01.280
by interacting with an environment, receiving&nbsp;
rewards or penalties based on its actions,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:01.280 --> 00:07:06.560
and continuously improving to maximize its&nbsp;
performance. For example, this type of learning&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:06.560 --> 00:07:11.920
is used to train AI in game-playing systems&nbsp;
like AlphaGo, or in self-driving cars, where&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:11.920 --> 00:07:17.960
the AI learns to navigate by trial and error.&nbsp;
Finally, there is deep learning. Deep learning&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:17.960 --> 00:07:23.160
is a specialized subset of machine learning that&nbsp;
uses artificial neural networks to handle large&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:23.160 --> 00:07:29.200
datasets and perform complex tasks. It’s inspired&nbsp;
by the way the human brain, a natural neural&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:29.200 --> 00:07:35.120
network, processes information. Once again,&nbsp;
AI is a broad field and machine learning is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:35.120 --> 00:07:40.880
a subset of AI that drives the most powerful AIs&nbsp;
that exist today, from large language models to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:40.880 --> 00:07:48.120
image recognition. Then, supervised, unsupervised,&nbsp;
reinforcement, and deep learning are subsets of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:48.120 --> 00:07:53.480
machine learning. We’ll take a look at each of&nbsp;
these learning methods in the following slides,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:53.480 --> 00:07:57.920
but keep in mind that these aren’t the only types&nbsp;
of machine learning. They’re just a few of the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:57.920 --> 00:08:02.880
most prominent examples, and they aren’t always&nbsp;
exclusive. They can be combined according to the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:02.880 --> 00:08:08.120
needs of the particular application. For example,&nbsp;
deep learning neural networks can be trained&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:08.120 --> 00:08:14.760
using any of the other three methods. Okay, now&nbsp;
let’s look deeper into each of these four types.

00:08:14.760 --> 00:08:20.520
We’ll start with supervised learning, which trains&nbsp;
the model on a labeled dataset. This means that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:20.520 --> 00:08:26.520
each input provided to the model for training has&nbsp;
a corresponding label. By examining these labeled&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:26.520 --> 00:08:31.200
examples, the model learns the relationship&nbsp;
between the data and its given labels,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:31.200 --> 00:08:37.120
building its understanding during the training&nbsp;
phase. For a simple example, let’s say we want to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:37.120 --> 00:08:43.040
train the model to differentiate between photos&nbsp;
of cats and photos of dogs. We start with a set&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:43.040 --> 00:08:49.320
of labeled training data, meaning each photo is&nbsp;
labeled as either “cat” or “dog”. To train an AI&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:49.320 --> 00:08:54.240
you should have more than eight photos of course,&nbsp;
but I’m just demonstrating the concept here. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:54.240 --> 00:08:59.560
you feed the labeled data into the model, and it&nbsp;
should, with enough data, build an understanding&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:59.560 --> 00:09:05.280
of what a cat looks like and what a dog&nbsp;
looks like. Once the model has been trained,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:05.280 --> 00:09:10.680
if you feed it an unlabeled photo of a dog, it&nbsp;
should be able to identify it as a dog. And it&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:10.680 --> 00:09:16.440
should be able to do the same for a photo of&nbsp;
a cat, too. By training on labeled examples,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:16.440 --> 00:09:23.520
the model learns to classify new, unseen data with&nbsp;
high accuracy. So, what are the main advantages&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:23.520 --> 00:09:29.360
and disadvantages of this method of machine&nbsp;
learning? Well, if labeled data is available,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:29.880 --> 00:09:35.160
supervised learning is highly accurate. When&nbsp;
training the model, it’s not going to misinterpret&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:35.160 --> 00:09:42.280
a cat as a dog, because the cat is already labeled&nbsp;
as a cat. But it requires large, labeled datasets,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:42.280 --> 00:09:47.200
which can be expensive and time-consuming&nbsp;
to create. As I said before, you’re going&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:47.200 --> 00:09:53.040
to need a lot more than eight photos to create&nbsp;
an accurate model. Another advantage is that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:53.040 --> 00:09:58.240
it’s straightforward to understand and implement.&nbsp;
The data is already labeled, so you just need to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:58.240 --> 00:10:02.600
train the model with as much data as possible&nbsp;
and it should develop a good understanding&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:02.600 --> 00:10:08.400
of each label’s characteristics. And one more&nbsp;
disadvantage is that the output is limited to the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:08.400 --> 00:10:14.640
labels in the training data. For example, if you&nbsp;
train the model only to classify cats and dogs,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:14.640 --> 00:10:20.640
it won’t be able recognize or classify a photo&nbsp;
of a bird. This means supervised learning isn’t&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:20.640 --> 00:10:28.680
ideal for tasks requiring flexibility&nbsp;
or identifying entirely new categories.

00:10:28.680 --> 00:10:33.040
Let’s move on to unsupervised learning,&nbsp;
which trains the model on an unlabeled&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:33.040 --> 00:10:39.720
dataset. This means that no predefined labels are&nbsp;
provided. Instead of being told what each data&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:39.720 --> 00:10:45.560
point represents, the model analyzes the data to&nbsp;
discover patterns, structures, or relationships on&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:45.560 --> 00:10:51.960
its own. It can then group similar data points&nbsp;
into clusters based on shared features. Let’s&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:51.960 --> 00:10:58.880
use the same example as before, feeding the model&nbsp;
photos of cats and dogs. In unsupervised learning,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:58.880 --> 00:11:04.440
we feed the model unlabeled training data, so the&nbsp;
images are provided without identifying them as&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:04.440 --> 00:11:10.200
"cat" or "dog". The model processes the data&nbsp;
and looks for patterns or similarities among&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:10.200 --> 00:11:17.120
the images. Based on its analysis, it groups the&nbsp;
images into clusters. Here, it has identified&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:17.120 --> 00:11:23.320
that the cat images all share similar features,&nbsp;
grouping them into cluster 1. The dog photos,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:23.320 --> 00:11:28.440
sharing their own set of features, are grouped&nbsp;
into cluster 2. It doesn’t know what these&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:28.440 --> 00:11:33.840
clusters represent. It simply groups similar&nbsp;
images together based on features like fur&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:33.840 --> 00:11:40.880
texture, shape, or color patterns. A human can&nbsp;
then interpret these clusters and label cluster&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:40.880 --> 00:11:48.000
1 as "cat”, and cluster 2 as “dog”. Then, if&nbsp;
you feed the model another image of a dog,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:48.000 --> 00:11:53.080
it should be able to recognize that it has similar&nbsp;
features to the other photos in cluster 2, and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:53.080 --> 00:11:59.520
assign it to that cluster. And same if you feed it&nbsp;
another photo of a cat. And if you feed it a photo&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:59.520 --> 00:12:05.720
that’s neither a cat nor a dog, like this bird, it&nbsp;
recognizes that it doesn’t fit into either cluster&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:05.720 --> 00:12:12.800
and creates a new one. And a human can once again&nbsp;
label that new cluster. So what are the advantages&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:12.800 --> 00:12:18.680
and disadvantages of unsupervised learning? One&nbsp;
big advantage is that there’s no need for labeled&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:18.680 --> 00:12:24.640
data, so that saves a lot of time and cost in&nbsp;
labeling huge data sets. But interpretation&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:24.640 --> 00:12:29.160
and labeling of the results by a human is&nbsp;
still required to make sense of the results.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:30.040 --> 00:12:33.640
Another benefit is that unsupervised&nbsp;
learning can reveal hidden patterns or&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:33.640 --> 00:12:39.160
structures in data that might not be obvious to&nbsp;
a human. For instance, it might group customers&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:39.160 --> 00:12:45.880
based on purchasing behavior, even if no explicit&nbsp;
labels exist. Because the data isn’t pre-labeled,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:45.880 --> 00:12:50.520
the model is free to group the data according&nbsp;
to what it notices, not according to the strict&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:50.520 --> 00:12:57.080
labels used in supervised learning. But without&nbsp;
labeled data, the model’s accuracy might be lower&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:57.080 --> 00:13:02.960
than supervised learning for specific tasks.&nbsp;
Unsupervised learning is a powerful tool for&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:02.960 --> 00:13:08.280
discovering patterns and relationships, especially&nbsp;
when labeled data isn’t available, but it requires&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:08.280 --> 00:13:15.840
human input to interpret results and might not&nbsp;
always match the precision of supervised learning.

00:13:15.840 --> 00:13:21.320
Next, let’s talk about reinforcement learning.&nbsp;
Reinforcement learning trains a model by rewarding&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:21.320 --> 00:13:27.160
or penalizing its actions in a given environment&nbsp;
to maximize its performance over time. The model&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:27.160 --> 00:13:32.600
learns to take actions within its environment that&nbsp;
achieve the highest reward or best outcome. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:32.600 --> 00:13:38.760
how does it work? First, the model, which is&nbsp;
called an agent, interacts with an environment.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:38.760 --> 00:13:44.400
It takes an action and receives feedback, which&nbsp;
could be either a reward for a positive action or&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:44.400 --> 00:13:51.280
a penalty for a negative one. For example, if the&nbsp;
AI is learning to play a game, actions that lead&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:51.280 --> 00:13:58.000
toward victory would be rewarded, and actions that&nbsp;
lead toward defeat will be penalized. The agent&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:58.000 --> 00:14:04.120
uses this feedback to adjust its behavior and&nbsp;
learn which actions lead to the best results. And&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:04.120 --> 00:14:10.480
the cycle repeats, allowing the model to improve&nbsp;
its ability to take the correct actions over time.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:10.480 --> 00:14:16.520
Let’s consider some examples of reinforcement&nbsp;
learning in action. In self-driving cars,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:16.520 --> 00:14:22.000
the agent learns how to navigate safely by trial&nbsp;
and error, earning rewards for avoiding obstacles&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:22.000 --> 00:14:28.600
or staying in the lane. In game AI, reinforcement&nbsp;
learning is used to master strategies in games&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:28.600 --> 00:14:35.520
like Chess, Go, or video games, where the agent&nbsp;
learns by playing and improving over time. And&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:35.520 --> 00:14:41.320
in robotics, agents can be trained to perform&nbsp;
complex tasks like walking, picking up objects,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:41.320 --> 00:14:47.080
or assembling items through reinforcement. Like&nbsp;
the other learning methods we covered, let’s&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:47.080 --> 00:14:53.440
consider a couple advantages and disadvantages.&nbsp;
It’s capable of learning complex behaviors that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:53.440 --> 00:14:59.400
are difficult to program manually. By allowing the&nbsp;
model to interact with the environment on its own,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:59.400 --> 00:15:03.880
it can learn these complex behaviors&nbsp;
without manual coding. But it can&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:03.880 --> 00:15:08.800
be quite resource-intensive, requiring&nbsp;
significant time and computational power,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:08.800 --> 00:15:14.440
especially for complex environments. The model has&nbsp;
to spend a lot of time and resources interacting&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:14.440 --> 00:15:20.600
with the environment. Another advantage is&nbsp;
that it adapts well to dynamic environments,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:20.600 --> 00:15:26.000
making it useful for tasks where conditions&nbsp;
are constantly changing. Through reinforcement,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:26.000 --> 00:15:32.280
the model can adapt automatically to changes. But&nbsp;
if the reward system isn’t carefully designed,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:32.280 --> 00:15:37.800
the agent might focus on short-term rewards&nbsp;
rather than the best long-term outcome. So&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:37.800 --> 00:15:41.680
the system of rewards and penalties&nbsp;
needs careful planning and design&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:41.680 --> 00:15:47.640
to avoid suboptimal learning. An interesting&nbsp;
example of reinforcement learning is MarI/O,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:48.560 --> 00:15:54.240
a program created by SethBling and shown in&nbsp;
a YouTube video. MarI/O uses reinforcement&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:54.240 --> 00:16:00.080
learning to teach itself how to play a level&nbsp;
of Super Mario World. It receives rewards for&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:00.080 --> 00:16:05.080
progressing through the level and, over many&nbsp;
evolutionary generations, builds a model that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:05.080 --> 00:16:10.880
can quickly and effectively navigate the level.&nbsp;
MarI/O is not only an example of reinforcement&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:10.880 --> 00:16:17.160
learning. It also applies the principles&nbsp;
of deep learning, which we’ll cover next.

00:16:17.160 --> 00:16:21.960
Deep learning is a subset of machine learning&nbsp;
that uses artificial neural networks to process&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:21.960 --> 00:16:28.200
and learn from large and complex datasets. An&nbsp;
artificial neural network is a computational&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:28.200 --> 00:16:34.720
model inspired by how biological neural networks&nbsp;
like the human brain process information. Data is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:34.720 --> 00:16:39.520
passed through multiple layers of interconnected&nbsp;
nodes, like the neurons in the human brain,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:39.520 --> 00:16:45.000
with each layer extracting increasingly abstract&nbsp;
features. These layers are what make deep learning&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:45.000 --> 00:16:50.000
so powerful. Note that deep learning isn’t&nbsp;
entirely separate from the other methods we’ve&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:50.000 --> 00:16:55.880
looked at. Neural networks used in deep learning&nbsp;
can be trained using supervised, unsupervised, or&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:55.880 --> 00:17:01.600
reinforcement methods. So, it’s essentially a more&nbsp;
advanced way of applying these approaches to solve&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:01.600 --> 00:17:08.200
complex problems. A deep learning model consists&nbsp;
of an input layer, which receives inputs like&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:08.200 --> 00:17:14.000
images. Then there are several “hidden layers”,&nbsp;
I’ve shown three here but there could be thousands&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:14.000 --> 00:17:20.320
in some models. And then there is an output layer.&nbsp;
And these layers are connected by a complex web of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:20.320 --> 00:17:26.960
connections, processing data from the input layer&nbsp;
and resulting in outputs in the output layer. For&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:26.960 --> 00:17:32.440
example, if the purpose of the model is image&nbsp;
recognition, if you feed it an image of a cat,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:32.440 --> 00:17:37.400
the result in the output layer should be “cat”. If&nbsp;
you want to learn about how Deep Learning really&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:37.400 --> 00:17:43.800
works, I recommend watching the neural networks&nbsp;
playlist by 3Blue1Brown on YouTube. It covers much&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:43.800 --> 00:17:48.520
more than you need to know for the CCNA exam,&nbsp;
but is a great primer on how deep learning and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:48.520 --> 00:17:56.440
neural networks work. So, what are the advantages&nbsp;
and disadvantages of deep learning? First of all,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:56.440 --> 00:18:03.080
it excels at handling large, unstructured datasets&nbsp;
like images, audio, and text. Data that doesn’t&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:03.080 --> 00:18:08.840
have a clear, predefined structure; it doesn’t fit&nbsp;
into traditional rows and columns of a database&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:08.840 --> 00:18:15.480
or spreadsheet. When it comes to tasks like&nbsp;
image recognition, natural language processing,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:15.480 --> 00:18:21.160
and autonomous driving, deep learning provides&nbsp;
state-of-the-art performance. But it can be quite&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:21.160 --> 00:18:25.840
resource-intensive, requiring significant&nbsp;
computational power and large datasets for&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:25.840 --> 00:18:30.840
training. And it’s often referred to as&nbsp;
a "black box" because the hidden layers&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:30.840 --> 00:18:35.640
make it hard to interpret how the model&nbsp;
arrives at its decisions. For instance,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:35.640 --> 00:18:41.040
while the model might identify a cat accurately,&nbsp;
it’s difficult to pinpoint which specific features&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:41.040 --> 00:18:46.480
it used to come to that conclusion. But&nbsp;
regardless of any drawbacks, deep learning&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:46.480 --> 00:18:51.920
is one of the most powerful tools in artificial&nbsp;
intelligence. Looking back again at MarI/O,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:52.880 --> 00:18:58.120
notice the neural network that it has built to&nbsp;
navigate through this stage of the game. While I&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:58.120 --> 00:19:03.440
showed MarI/O as an example of reinforcement&nbsp;
learning, it uses reinforcement to train an&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:03.440 --> 00:19:11.040
artificial neural network, although deep learning&nbsp;
models typically use many more layers than this.

00:19:11.040 --> 00:19:14.760
So, those are the main types of machine&nbsp;
learning we’ll cover in this video:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:14.760 --> 00:19:20.600
supervised, unsupervised, reinforcement,&nbsp;
and deep learning. As I mentioned before,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:20.600 --> 00:19:26.360
these aren’t the only types of machine learning,&nbsp;
and models can use combinations of these methods.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:26.360 --> 00:19:30.680
For example, deep learning models can be&nbsp;
trained using supervised, unsupervised,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:30.680 --> 00:19:36.680
or reinforcement learning techniques. There’s also&nbsp;
semi-supervised learning, which combines labeled&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:36.680 --> 00:19:41.840
and unlabeled data, enjoying the benefits&nbsp;
of both methods. But these four types are&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:41.840 --> 00:19:47.600
what I recommend knowing for the CCNA exam. Now,&nbsp;
let’s move on to predictive and generative AI,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:47.600 --> 00:19:55.520
two key applications of AI that take advantage of&nbsp;
machine learning, and especially deep learning.

00:19:55.520 --> 00:20:00.960
Before we dive into each, let’s briefly define&nbsp;
them. Predictive AI uses machine learning to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:00.960 --> 00:20:07.080
analyze historical data and predict future&nbsp;
outcomes or trends. A couple of examples are&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:07.080 --> 00:20:13.360
security anomaly detection in a network, or&nbsp;
weather forecasting. And generative AI uses&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:13.360 --> 00:20:19.480
machine learning to learn patterns from existing&nbsp;
data and create new content, such as text, images,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:19.480 --> 00:20:25.720
or audio. Some well-known examples are&nbsp;
ChatGPT and Gemini for text generation,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:25.720 --> 00:20:28.640
or Midjourney and DALL-E for image generation.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:30.160 --> 00:20:35.400
This diagram shows where predictive and generative&nbsp;
AI fit within the fields of AI, machine learning,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:35.400 --> 00:20:40.920
and deep learning. While the most powerful&nbsp;
predictive and generative AIs today rely on deep&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:40.920 --> 00:20:48.720
learning, simpler AIs can also exist outside deep&nbsp;
learning, using other machine learning methods.

00:20:48.720 --> 00:20:54.840
Now let’s look a bit deeper into predictive&nbsp;
AI. Predictive AI analyzes historical data&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:54.840 --> 00:21:02.320
to forecast future outcomes, trends, or events. It&nbsp;
identifies patterns and correlations in past data,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:02.320 --> 00:21:07.880
and applies those learned patterns to&nbsp;
make predictions about new or future data.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:07.880 --> 00:21:14.880
Predictive AI is very widely used for a variety&nbsp;
of applications. Let’s list a few. In healthcare,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:14.880 --> 00:21:18.520
it can predict patient outcomes&nbsp;
or the progression of diseases,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:18.520 --> 00:21:24.920
helping doctors make better treatment decisions.&nbsp;
For example, AI can analyze an X-ray to identify&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:24.920 --> 00:21:31.200
diseases earlier than a doctor might in many&nbsp;
cases. In network security, it’s used to detect&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:31.200 --> 00:21:37.720
anomalies that might indicate potential threats&nbsp;
or failures. It’s also used in traffic management,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:37.720 --> 00:21:43.120
where it can predict congestion based on both&nbsp;
historical and real-time traffic data. I’m&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:43.120 --> 00:21:48.120
referring to road traffic here, but predictive&nbsp;
AI can play the same role for network traffic,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:48.120 --> 00:21:53.240
predicting congestion or potential&nbsp;
bottlenecks based on usage patterns.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:53.240 --> 00:21:59.600
Businesses rely on predictive AI for forecasting&nbsp;
sales trends or understanding customer behavior,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:59.600 --> 00:22:06.120
and meteorologists use it for weather forecasting,&nbsp;
analyzing data to predict future conditions. Okay,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:06.120 --> 00:22:11.120
those are just a few examples of predictive&nbsp;
AI, now let’s consider its advantages and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:11.120 --> 00:22:17.640
disadvantages. It improves decision-making by&nbsp;
providing actionable insights, enabling you to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:17.640 --> 00:22:24.600
detect potential problems before they occur, such&nbsp;
as network issues or severe weather. But to do so,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:24.600 --> 00:22:30.280
it requires high-quality and relevant historical&nbsp;
data to be accurate. Without significant amounts&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:30.280 --> 00:22:36.800
of high-quality data, the AI isn’t likely to make&nbsp;
accurate predictions. And its performance depends&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:36.800 --> 00:22:43.240
on how well the patterns in past data generalize&nbsp;
to new scenarios. If the future is significantly&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:43.240 --> 00:22:49.640
different from the past, the model may&nbsp;
struggle to make accurate predictions.

00:22:49.640 --> 00:22:55.360
Now let’s look at generative AI, which is&nbsp;
quite popular these days for a variety of uses.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:55.360 --> 00:23:01.600
Generative AI learns patterns from existing data&nbsp;
and creates new content, such as text, images,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:01.600 --> 00:23:07.400
and audio. It focuses on producing outputs&nbsp;
that resemble the input it was trained on,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:07.400 --> 00:23:14.480
but are entirely new creations. For example, let’s&nbsp;
say we train a generative AI model on labeled data&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:14.480 --> 00:23:21.160
of cats and dogs. This model learns the features&nbsp;
of these animals. Then, if we give it a prompt,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:21.160 --> 00:23:27.680
like “Generate an image of a cat,” the AI uses its&nbsp;
understanding of patterns in cat images to create&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:27.680 --> 00:23:34.080
an entirely new picture of a cat that didn’t exist&nbsp;
before. So, let’s consider some applications of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:34.080 --> 00:23:41.560
generative AI. In text generation, tools like&nbsp;
ChatGPT, Gemini, and Copilot can generate&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:41.560 --> 00:23:47.680
human-like text for tasks such as answering&nbsp;
questions, writing code, or writing emails.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:47.680 --> 00:23:55.880
These are called large language models, LLMs. For&nbsp;
image generation, AIs like Midjourney and DALL-E&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:55.880 --> 00:24:03.160
create detailed artwork from text prompts, like&nbsp;
the diagram above. And in video generation, tools&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:03.160 --> 00:24:11.040
like OpenAI’s Sora and Google’s Veo 2 can generate&nbsp;
realistic videos based on user input. Now,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:11.040 --> 00:24:17.360
let’s look at its advantages and disadvantages.&nbsp;
First of all, it’s great for creative tasks where&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:17.360 --> 00:24:24.200
human input is limited or time-consuming. For&nbsp;
example, a generative AI chatbot can take over&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:24.200 --> 00:24:31.160
a lot of online customer service from humans, only&nbsp;
escalating to a human when necessary. Generative&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:31.160 --> 00:24:36.840
AI enables the automation of content creation&nbsp;
across various fields. But this, of course,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:36.840 --> 00:24:45.040
has its downsides. There is a major risk of&nbsp;
misuse, such as deepfakes and plagiarism. There’s&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:45.040 --> 00:24:50.200
also the problem that generated content is only&nbsp;
as good as the quality of the training material,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:50.200 --> 00:24:56.200
as well as the model itself. Let’s be honest,&nbsp;
there’s a lot of AI slop out there. I’ve even seen&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:56.200 --> 00:25:03.760
an entirely AI-generated CCNA course. Fortunately&nbsp;
for me, AI isn’t ready to take my job just yet,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:03.760 --> 00:25:09.400
but that could very well change in the future. And&nbsp;
since I mentioned the material used to train these&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:09.400 --> 00:25:15.560
AIs, there are serious copyright issues regarding&nbsp;
these models, both in the data used to train them&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:15.560 --> 00:25:21.160
and in the outputs they generate. Finally, one&nbsp;
more thing worth mentioning is the problem of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:21.160 --> 00:25:27.000
hallucinations; basically, making up answers that&nbsp;
are totally incorrect. This is the main reason why&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:27.000 --> 00:25:32.720
I recommend avoiding large language models like&nbsp;
ChatGPT when you’re studying for the CCNA. It&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:32.720 --> 00:25:38.240
just isn’t reliable enough. But regardless,&nbsp;
generative AI is clearly a very effective&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:38.240 --> 00:25:45.800
tool that many of us use daily for various&nbsp;
tasks, and it will only get better from here.

00:25:45.800 --> 00:25:51.000
So far in this video, we’ve looked at AI and&nbsp;
machine learning from a more general perspective,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:51.000 --> 00:25:57.040
but let’s move on to consider some applications of&nbsp;
predictive and generative AI to networking. First,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:57.040 --> 00:26:02.440
here are a few ways that predictive AI can be&nbsp;
applied to networking. Traffic forecasting is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:02.440 --> 00:26:08.040
one application. By analyzing past traffic&nbsp;
patterns, AI can predict future patterns,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:08.040 --> 00:26:14.120
providing insights into how to optimize bandwidth&nbsp;
allocation and prevent congestion. For example,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:14.120 --> 00:26:18.800
the AI could advise you to increase the&nbsp;
bandwidth of a particular link with EtherChannel,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:18.800 --> 00:26:25.160
or optimize the QoS policy to allow important&nbsp;
traffic to get through without delay. Security&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:25.160 --> 00:26:31.120
threat detection is another important application.&nbsp;
If the AI notices anomalies, it can predict that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:31.120 --> 00:26:37.240
an attack is occurring or about to occur, helping&nbsp;
to minimize the damage. It can also be applied&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:37.240 --> 00:26:42.520
to what’s called predictive maintenance. By&nbsp;
anticipating hardware failures in advance,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:42.520 --> 00:26:49.320
you can proactively replace faulty hardware before&nbsp;
it causes a major issue. And what about generative&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:49.320 --> 00:26:54.760
AI? It has several uses, and I’ll demonstrate&nbsp;
a few ways you can use ChatGPT for some of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:54.760 --> 00:27:01.320
these applications as well. First, you can use&nbsp;
generative AI for documentation. For example,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:01.320 --> 00:27:06.040
by providing information about your network and&nbsp;
its configurations, the AI can automatically&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:06.040 --> 00:27:11.520
generate documentation for your network. Or&nbsp;
you can use AI to help with generating the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:11.520 --> 00:27:18.080
configurations themselves based on the policies&nbsp;
and requirements you provide. For example, in this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:18.080 --> 00:27:24.400
clip I provide a simple network diagram to ChatGPT&nbsp;
and ask it to generate configurations that enable&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:24.400 --> 00:27:30.360
full connectivity in the network. The generated&nbsp;
configurations can then be copied and pasted into&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:30.360 --> 00:27:37.760
the devices, after verifying that they’re correct,&nbsp;
of course. Another application is network design.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:37.760 --> 00:27:44.680
Generative AI can suggest designs tailored to your&nbsp;
specific needs, offering advice and optimizations.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:44.680 --> 00:27:50.600
Troubleshooting is another useful application. You&nbsp;
can provide log files or error messages and get&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:50.600 --> 00:27:57.520
help in the troubleshooting process. For example,&nbsp;
in this clip I share a log message with ChatGPT,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:57.520 --> 00:28:02.840
and it outlines the cause of the message, as&nbsp;
well as steps to fix the issue. You should&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:02.840 --> 00:28:08.080
always verify what ChatGPT says, don’t follow&nbsp;
it blindly, but it can be very helpful in the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:08.080 --> 00:28:15.240
troubleshooting process. And the last use case&nbsp;
I’ll mention for now is script generation. You&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:15.240 --> 00:28:20.200
can use AI to automatically generate network&nbsp;
automation scripts, such as Python scripts to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:20.200 --> 00:28:27.200
configure network devices. In other words, you&nbsp;
can automate your automation. In this clip I do&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:27.200 --> 00:28:34.400
just that, asking ChatGPT to generate a script&nbsp;
to configure a router. Let me repeat myself:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:34.400 --> 00:28:39.920
always double-check before using anything ChatGPT&nbsp;
gives you in a real network, as it can hallucinate&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:39.920 --> 00:28:47.560
and make mistakes. But there’s no doubt that it&nbsp;
has many very useful applications to networking.

00:28:47.560 --> 00:28:53.040
Finally, let’s cover some features of Cisco&nbsp;
Catalyst Center that leverage AI. Although&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:53.040 --> 00:28:58.160
the exam topics list doesn’t say you need to know&nbsp;
these AI features for the exam, it’s good to have&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:58.160 --> 00:29:04.200
a general idea of how Catalyst Center uses AI.&nbsp;
So, Catalyst Center, which used to be called DNA&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:04.200 --> 00:29:10.440
Center, features a variety of AI-enabled features&nbsp;
to identify issues before they impact users,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:10.440 --> 00:29:15.040
reduce the time required to resolve issues,&nbsp;
and increase the performance and security of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:15.040 --> 00:29:21.160
the network. I’ll list some of the features and&nbsp;
then show what some of them look like in Catalyst&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:21.160 --> 00:29:26.840
Center’s GUI, but if you want a more detailed&nbsp;
look you can check out this video from Cisco,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:26.840 --> 00:29:32.400
Discovering the secrets of AI and ML in Cisco&nbsp;
Catalyst Center. I made this short link that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:32.400 --> 00:29:41.080
will redirect you to it, jitl.jp/cat-ai, or you&nbsp;
can just google the title to find it. You don’t&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:41.080 --> 00:29:47.920
have to know everything covered in this video for&nbsp;
the CCNA, but check it out if you’re interested.

00:29:47.920 --> 00:29:53.560
So, what are some of those AI features in&nbsp;
Catalyst Center? One is AI Network Analytics,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:53.560 --> 00:29:58.480
which is actually an umbrella term that includes&nbsp;
several other features within it. Basically,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:58.480 --> 00:30:03.600
it’s all about using AI, specifically machine&nbsp;
learning, to establish the baseline behavior&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:03.600 --> 00:30:09.360
of the network. In other words, it determines&nbsp;
what is considered “normal” for this network.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:09.360 --> 00:30:12.440
It can then provide insights and&nbsp;
recommendations for optimizing the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:12.440 --> 00:30:19.320
network, and monitor to predict and detect&nbsp;
anomalies, things outside of the baseline.

00:30:19.320 --> 00:30:25.480
Here’s a screenshot showing one small part of&nbsp;
AI Network Analytics. As the legend here shows,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:25.480 --> 00:30:29.280
green indicates the predicted&nbsp;
value, or rather range of values,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:29.280 --> 00:30:34.000
which is the baseline that has been&nbsp;
established. And blue shows the actual value,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:34.000 --> 00:30:39.120
in this case the amount of time it took&nbsp;
hosts to lease an address with DHCP. And&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:39.120 --> 00:30:45.160
the bottom two graphs show the same thing for&nbsp;
authentication and association times; this data&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:45.160 --> 00:30:52.720
here is about Wi-Fi connections, but AI Network&nbsp;
Analytics is not limited to Wi-Fi, of course.

00:30:52.720 --> 00:30:58.600
And now let’s continue with the Machine Reasoning&nbsp;
Engine, MRE, which uses AI to perform root-cause&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:58.600 --> 00:31:05.600
analysis when network issues arise. It can then&nbsp;
suggest resolutions or take automated corrective&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:05.600 --> 00:31:11.280
actions to fix the issue. So, this reduces&nbsp;
downtime by identifying and resolving issues&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:11.280 --> 00:31:16.800
faster than traditional methods. Traditional&nbsp;
methods might be something like a user complains&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:16.800 --> 00:31:22.240
about a network issue, you investigate and try&nbsp;
to identify the issue, make some sort of change&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:22.240 --> 00:31:30.400
to remedy it, and then hope it solves the problem.&nbsp;
MRE can potentially automate that entire process.

00:31:30.400 --> 00:31:35.360
Here’s a quick look at MRE in&nbsp;
action. MRE identified an issue,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:35.360 --> 00:31:41.280
an interface that is down. Here you can see&nbsp;
its reasoning process; the root cause analysis&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:41.280 --> 00:31:47.320
that it performs to identify what caused the&nbsp;
issue. And you can see more details here. Now,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:47.320 --> 00:31:51.960
I don’t have access to Catalyst Center with&nbsp;
MRE in my lab, so I got this screenshot from&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:51.960 --> 00:31:56.960
this presentation from Cisco, by the way. If&nbsp;
you want to know more about Catalyst Center,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:56.960 --> 00:32:03.360
Cisco has plenty of documentation and&nbsp;
video demos, so they’re worth checking out.

00:32:03.360 --> 00:32:09.760
Okay, next we have AI Endpoint Analytics. As&nbsp;
the name suggests, this focuses on endpoints,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:09.760 --> 00:32:16.280
the devices connected to the network. AI endpoint&nbsp;
analytics identifies and classifies devices on the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:16.280 --> 00:32:22.680
network, providing detailed visibility into those&nbsp;
devices and what they’re doing on the network.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:22.680 --> 00:32:28.040
It detects unauthorized devices or unusual&nbsp;
behavior, for example identifying devices engaged&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:28.040 --> 00:32:33.440
in malicious behavior on the network. And it&nbsp;
simplifies device onboarding by automating&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:33.440 --> 00:32:38.880
profiling and segmentation. What that means&nbsp;
is, when a device connects to the network,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:38.880 --> 00:32:43.600
Catalyst Center can identify what kind of&nbsp;
device it is and apply appropriate security&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:43.600 --> 00:32:51.720
policies. This enhances security and also simply&nbsp;
reduces workload by automating these tasks. Okay,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:51.720 --> 00:32:55.600
the final feature I’ll mention is&nbsp;
AI-enhanced radio resource management,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:55.600 --> 00:33:02.320
RRM. This is referring to Wi-Fi: it optimizes&nbsp;
wireless network performance by dynamically&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:02.320 --> 00:33:09.240
adjusting radio settings on access points. And&nbsp;
it uses AI to balance load among different APs,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:09.240 --> 00:33:12.080
reduce interference through&nbsp;
appropriate channel selection,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:12.080 --> 00:33:18.560
and improve coverage by automatically adjusting&nbsp;
the transmit power of each access point.

00:33:18.560 --> 00:33:25.080
Here’s one small look at AI-enhanced RRM. Here&nbsp;
we see statistics about channel utilization and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:25.080 --> 00:33:33.680
interference. And down here some more data about&nbsp;
RRM. Notice here it states RRM changes: changes&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:33.680 --> 00:33:40.040
that AI has made to optimize Wi-Fi performance in&nbsp;
the LAN. Okay, that’s all for our quick look at&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:40.040 --> 00:33:47.040
AI in Catalyst Center. Cisco has several products&nbsp;
that incorporate AI in a variety of ways, but for&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:47.040 --> 00:33:54.920
the CCNA you should just focus on the basics of&nbsp;
AI and machine learning we covered in this video.

00:33:54.920 --> 00:34:01.400
Before moving on to the quiz, let’s summarize&nbsp;
what we covered. Artificial intelligence, AI,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:01.400 --> 00:34:07.400
uses computers to simulate intelligence, capable&nbsp;
of pattern recognition, learning, problem solving,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:07.400 --> 00:34:14.680
and other tasks. Machine learning, ML, is a&nbsp;
subset of AI that focuses on enabling computers to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:14.680 --> 00:34:21.120
automatically learn from data and improve without&nbsp;
the need for explicit programming. But like AI,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:21.120 --> 00:34:27.520
ML is a wide field and there are a variety of ways&nbsp;
that a computer can learn. We covered four. The&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:27.520 --> 00:34:33.080
first was supervised learning, in which the model&nbsp;
is trained on labeled data to make predictions or&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:33.080 --> 00:34:39.480
classifications on new data. I used the example&nbsp;
of training the AI on labeled photos of dogs and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:39.480 --> 00:34:45.200
cats. Then there’s unsupervised learning, in&nbsp;
which the model is trained on unlabeled data&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:45.200 --> 00:34:50.160
to find patterns, relationships, or groupings in&nbsp;
the data on its own without a human labeling the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:50.160 --> 00:34:56.720
data beforehand. In reinforcement learning, the&nbsp;
model learns by interacting with an environment,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:56.720 --> 00:35:03.400
and receiving penalties or rewards based on its&nbsp;
actions. Self-driving cars and game AIs are great&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:03.400 --> 00:35:10.080
applications of this. Finally, deep learning uses&nbsp;
multi-layered neural networks, inspired by how the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:10.080 --> 00:35:15.600
human brain works, to handle large datasets and&nbsp;
perform complex tasks; more than is typically&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:15.600 --> 00:35:21.360
possible with other forms of machine learning.&nbsp;
Okay, next we covered predictive and generative&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:21.360 --> 00:35:27.880
AI. Predictive AI uses machine learning to analyze&nbsp;
historical data and predict future outcomes&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:27.880 --> 00:35:34.200
or trends. In networking, this can be applied to&nbsp;
network traffic forecasting, threat detection,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:34.200 --> 00:35:39.720
and predictive maintenance, to give a few&nbsp;
examples. And generative AI uses machine learning&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:39.720 --> 00:35:46.760
to learn patterns from existing data and create&nbsp;
new content, such as text and images. ChatGPT&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:46.760 --> 00:35:52.960
and other popular large language models are good&nbsp;
examples of this. In networking, a few possible&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:52.960 --> 00:35:57.640
applications are configuration generation,&nbsp;
troubleshooting, and script generation.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:59.040 --> 00:36:04.560
This diagram shows the position of predictive and&nbsp;
generative AI within the fields of deep learning,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:04.560 --> 00:36:11.320
machine learning, and AI as a whole. Finally,&nbsp;
I introduced a few AI-enablde features of Cisco&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:11.320 --> 00:36:18.160
Catalyst Center. The four I focused on were AI&nbsp;
network analytics, the machine reasoning engine,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:18.160 --> 00:36:23.560
AI endpoint analytics, and AI-enhanced&nbsp;
radio resource management. Okay,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:23.560 --> 00:36:30.840
that’s all we covered in the video. Now let’s move&nbsp;
on to a quick quiz to test your understanding.

00:36:30.840 --> 00:36:35.200
Here’s quiz question one. Which of&nbsp;
the following types of ML imitates&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:35.200 --> 00:36:42.920
the human brain? Pause the video&nbsp;
now to think about your answer.

00:36:42.920 --> 00:36:47.920
Okay, the answer is C, deep learning. Deep&nbsp;
learning mimics the structure and functioning&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:47.920 --> 00:36:53.240
of the human brain by using artificial neural&nbsp;
networks with multiple layers. These networks&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:53.240 --> 00:36:58.440
process information hierarchically, similar to how&nbsp;
the brain processes data, enabling deep learning&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:58.440 --> 00:37:05.800
models to identify complex patterns and make&nbsp;
predictions. Okay, let’s go to the next question.

00:37:05.800 --> 00:37:08.680
Here’s question 2. Which of the following Catalyst&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:37:08.680 --> 00:37:13.600
Center features leverages AI to perform&nbsp;
a root-cause analysis of network issues&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:37:13.600 --> 00:37:22.480
and propose resolutions? Pause the&nbsp;
video now to think about your answer.

00:37:22.480 --> 00:37:29.160
Okay, the answer is C, MRE, which stands for&nbsp;
Machine Reasoning Engine. MRE leverages AI to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:37:29.160 --> 00:37:34.760
perform root-cause analysis of network issues&nbsp;
and propose resolutions. It can also take&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:37:34.760 --> 00:37:42.120
automated corrective actions to resolve issues&nbsp;
without human intervention. Okay, next question.

00:37:42.120 --> 00:37:45.360
Here’s question 3. Which of the&nbsp;
following statements are true?&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:37:45.360 --> 00:37:53.880
Select three. Pause the video&nbsp;
now to think about your answers.

00:37:53.880 --> 00:37:58.800
Okay, the correct answers are A, D, and&nbsp;
F. Reinforcement learning relies on a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:37:58.800 --> 00:38:04.520
reward/penalty system to train models based on&nbsp;
actions taken. It is particularly effective for&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:38:04.520 --> 00:38:10.480
game AIs, where agents learn strategies by&nbsp;
maximizing rewards. Unsupervised learning&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:38:10.480 --> 00:38:15.000
uses unlabeled datasets to find patterns&nbsp;
in data, unlike supervised learning,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:38:15.000 --> 00:38:20.520
which requires labeled data. B is incorrect&nbsp;
because supervised learning works with data&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:38:20.520 --> 00:38:24.480
that is already labeled and is not&nbsp;
suited to discovering hidden patterns;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:38:24.480 --> 00:38:30.120
unsupervised learning is better for that. C is&nbsp;
incorrect because, although the most powerful&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:38:30.120 --> 00:38:35.040
predictive and generative AIs use deep learning,&nbsp;
it’s not a strict requirement for a predictive or&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:38:35.040 --> 00:38:41.240
generative AI. And E is incorrect as supervised&nbsp;
and unsupervised learning can complement each&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:38:41.240 --> 00:38:47.200
other, and this is called semi-supervised&nbsp;
learning. Okay, that’s all for the quiz.

00:38:47.200 --> 00:38:52.320
And that’s all for this video on AI and machine&nbsp;
learning. While a fundamental understanding of&nbsp;&nbsp;

